%N A180319 Total number of possible standard knight moves on an n X 2n chessboard, if the knight is placed anywhere.
%C A180319 a(n) counts every possible moves of a standard chess knight placed anywhere.
%C A180319 For examples, in usual chessboard 8X8 a knight in a corner has only 2 moves,
%C A180319 in a central square it has the maximum number of moves:8.
%C A180319 Summing all over the 64 squares we have 336 possible moves.
%C A180319 Instead on a chessboard 4x8 the number is reduced:
%C A180319 -----------------
%C A180319 |2|3|4|4|4|4|3|2|
%C A180319 -----------------
%C A180319 |3|4|6|6|6|6|4|3|
%C A180319 -----------------
%C A180319 |3|4|6|6|6|6|4|3|
%C A180319 -----------------
%C A180319 |2|3|4|4|4|4|3|2|
%C A180319 -----------------
%C A180319 the total number is 128
%F A180319 Conjecture: a(n) = 4*(4-9*n+4*n^2) for n>1. a(n) = 3*a(n-1)-3*a(n-2)+a(n-3) for n>4. G.f.: 4*x^2*(2+7*x-x^2)/(1-x)^3. [Colin Barker, Mar 11 2012]
